# Methods in Java

Imagine a coffee machine. You press one button and the entire brewing sequence — heating water, grinding beans, extracting espresso — runs automatically. You do not repeat the steps every time. A **method** in Java works the same way: you write a block of code once, give it a name, and call it by that name whenever you need it.

## Method Anatomy

```java
access_modifier return_type methodName(parameters) {
    // method body
    return value;  // if return_type is not void
}
```

```java
public static int add(int a, int b) {
    return a + b;
}
```

- `public` — access modifier (visible everywhere)
- `static` — belongs to the class, not an object instance
- `int` — return type (the type of value this method sends back)
- `add` — the method name (camelCase convention)
- `int a, int b` — parameters (typed input variables)
- `return a + b` — the result sent back to the caller

## void Methods — No Return Value

If a method produces output (like printing) but has no value to return, use `void`:

```java
public static void printSeparator(int length) {
    for (int i = 0; i < length; i++) {
        System.out.print("-");
    }
    System.out.println();
}
```

## Calling a Method

```java
public static void main(String[] args) {
    int result = add(10, 5);        // result = 15
    System.out.println(result);
    printSeparator(20);             // calls void method
}
```

## Parameters vs Arguments

- **Parameter** — the variable declared in the method definition (`int a`)
- **Argument** — the actual value passed when calling the method (`10`)

## Why Methods Matter

- **No repetition** — write the logic once, use it everywhere
- **Testability** — each method can be tested independently
- **Readability** — `calculateGST(price)` is clearer than 15 lines of arithmetic
- **Maintainability** — fix a bug once in the method and it is fixed everywhere

In the code example below, you will see a complete set of utility methods for an invoice system, demonstrating void methods, return methods, and method calling patterns.

codeExample.code:
public class Main {

    // void method — no return value
    public static void printHeader(String title) {
        System.out.println("==============================");
        System.out.println("  " + title);
        System.out.println("==============================");
    }

    // Returns a double — calculated result
    public static double calculateTotal(double price, int qty) {
        return price * qty;
    }

    // Returns a double — applies GST
    public static double applyGST(double subtotal, double rate) {
        return subtotal * (1 + rate);
    }

    // Returns a String — letter grade
    public static String getGrade(int score) {
        if      (score >= 90) return "A";
        else if (score >= 80) return "B";
        else if (score >= 70) return "C";
        else                  return "F";
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        printHeader("GST Invoice");

        double subtotal = calculateTotal(1250.0, 4);   // 5000.0
        double total    = applyGST(subtotal, 0.18);    // 5900.0

        System.out.printf("Subtotal : Rs %.2f%n", subtotal);
        System.out.printf("Total    : Rs %.2f%n", total);

        // Methods can be called multiple times with different arguments
        System.out.println("Grade 95 : " + getGrade(95));
        System.out.println("Grade 72 : " + getGrade(72));
    }
}

